riting, they do so in full awareness that the trajectory it dictates leads not to metaphysical redemption but rather downward, into the uncanny element of fiction. As this book argues, the sublime has always been a deeply melancholy affair, even in its classical Kantian form, but it is in the attenuated speech of narrative voices progressively stripped of their resources and rewards that the true nature of this melancholy is revealed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aSublime, The, in literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aFranz Kafka.  aImmanuel Kant.  aJean-Luc Nancy.  aMartin Heidegger.  aMaurice Blanchot.  aPhilippe Lacoue-Labarthe.  aSamuel Beckett.  acategorical imperative.  adeath mask.  aliterature and philosophy.  aschematism.  asublime.  awriting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311072903040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823254712zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823254712423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823254712/original  a978-3-11-072903-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK